ry materiality has been dominated by an ideology of modernism, based on the ideal of the autonomous work of art, which has hindered our ability to read poetry as a socially critical medium. By focusing on writing as a palimpsest involving numerous layers of materiality--from the holograph manuscript to the printed book--Davidson exposes modern poetry's engagement with larger historical forces. The palimpsest that results is less a poem than an arrested stage of writing in whose layers can be discerned ghostly traces of other texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFantasy in literature. 0aGhosts in literature. 0aIrrationalism (Philosophy) in literature. 0aMaterialism in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aSupernatural in literature. 4aAmerican literature. 4aEnglish Literature. 4aaesthetics. 4ahistory of literature. 4aideology. 4aliterary theory. 4aliterature. 4amateriality. 4apoet. 4apoetics. 4apoetry. 4atext. 4atheory of literature. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052030868840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520313194?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520313194423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520313194/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles